## Abstract
Grid collapse and fuel supply failure are recurring crises across the developing world and in disaster-affected regions. Haiti, Yemen, Sudan, Gaza, Puerto Rico, rural sub-Saharan Africa, post-typhoon Pacific island communities — the pattern repeats: external energy dependence fails, and communities are left without power for hospitals, water pumping, food storage, and communications.
This document presents a complete technical specification for the Global Resonance Generator (GRG-10K): a decentralized, fuel-independent power generation system delivering 2–4 kW of continuous power from ambient thermal gradients, with zero fuel input, zero combustion, and minimal maintenance over a 20–25 year operational lifespan.
Version 1.2 introduces two additions beyond the original specification: an **Atmospheric Water Generation
(AWG)** cogeneration module that harvests condensate from the thermoelectric cold side, and a **Data Center Thermal Integration Variant** that replaces solar-thermal collection with data center exhaust heat, enabling continuous 24/7 generation independent of solar irradiance cycles.
The document additionally presents the **Eido-Bolt Phase Array** as an experimental enhancement module. The Eido-Bolt is presented transparently as an R&D hypothesis. The base system functions and delivers value without it.
---
## 1. The Problem This Solves
Energy poverty and grid vulnerability affect an estimated 750 million people globally who lack reliable electricity access, and hundreds of millions more who experience frequent outages due to infrastructure failure, conflict, or natural disaster.
Existing humanitarian energy responses typically rely on diesel generators — which require continuous fuel supply chains that are often the first thing to fail in a crisis — or large-scale solar installations that require specialized installation teams and are vulnerable to storm damage.
The GRG-10K is designed around a different premise: a power system that requires nothing from outside the community to operate. No fuel. No replacement parts for years. Harvestable energy from heat sources that every community on earth has access to daily.
### 1.1 Design Criteria
-	**Zero ongoing fuel requirement** — must operate indefinitely on ambient energy
-	**Field-repairable** — any component replaceable by a technician with basic electronics skills
-	**Climate resilient** — operable in tropical heat, coastal salt air, and hurricane-force winds
-	**Grid-flexible** — configurable for 110V or 220V, 50Hz or 60Hz
-	**Locally sourceable** — major components available through regional supply chains in most of the world
-	**Scalable** — from single household (2 kW) to community microgrid (50–100 kW) without redesign
