## 2. System Architecture Overview
The GRG-10K harvests the temperature differential between a heat source and ambient air, converts it to electricity via thermoelectric modules, and conditions that electricity for direct use or grid feed-in.
```
[Heat Source — Solar Thermal OR Data Center Exhaust]
                    │
                    ▼
         [Thermoelectric Array]
         Bi₂Te₃ / Mg₂Si segmented
         256 couples, 400 cm² active area
                    │
                    ▼
         [Power Electronics]
         Active rectifier + grid-tie inverter
         DC link: 400V regulated
                    │
          ┌─────────┴─────────┐
          │                   │
      [Battery]          [Axial Flux]
      LiFePO₄           Motor-Generator
      10 kWh            PCB stator, Halbach rotor
      buffer            Magnetic levitation bearings
          │                   │
          └─────────┬─────────┘
                    │
         [Grid Interface / Load]
         Configurable: 110V–240V / 50Hz–60Hz
         Island mode + grid-tie
                    │
          ┌─────────┴─────────┐
          │                   │
  [Refrigeration]          [AWG Module]
  Cold-side cogeneration    Condensate collection
  Medication / food storage Potable water output
```
### 2.1 Solar Thermal Variant (Standard Deployment)
In the standard configuration, a flat-plate solar thermal collector (4 m²) provides the hot side of the thermoelectric gradient. Hot-side temperature reaches 60–120°C under direct irradiance, against a cold-side ambient of 20–40°C. Output is highest during daylight hours; the 10 kWh LiFePO₄ buffer sustains load through the night.
This configuration is appropriate for off-grid humanitarian deployments in regions without existing infrastructure.
### 2.2 Data Center Thermal Integration Variant
In data center environments, server hardware generates continuous waste heat as a byproduct of computation. Hot-aisle exhaust typically runs at 35–45°C; liquid-cooled manifolds and direct chip-contact heat sinks can reach 60–80°C. This heat is currently dissipated as a liability. The GRG-10K treats it as fuel.
In this variant, the flat-plate solar collector is replaced by a **heat exchanger manifold** mounted in the data center exhaust plenum. The manifold transfers exhaust heat to the thermoelectric array hot side via a liquidto-air or air-to-air coupling interface, depending on the facility's cooling topology.
**Thermodynamic comparison:**
| Parameter | Solar Thermal Variant | Data Center Variant |
|---|---|---|
| Hot-side temp | 60–120°C (peak, daytime) | 45–80°C (continuous) |
| Cold-side temp | 20–40°C ambient | 20–30°C facility ambient |
| ΔT | 30–80°C variable | 25–50°C stable |
| Generation profile | Diurnal, weather-dependent | 24/7, load-dependent |
| Battery utilization | Required for overnight | Minimal — buffer only |
| AWG yield context | Outdoor humidity | Facility humidity (variable) |
The data center variant trades peak ΔT for **continuous ΔT**. Solar thermal can produce a higher instantaneous gradient under ideal conditions; data center exhaust provides a lower but constant gradient that never drops to zero. For buffer management and grid stability, flat continuous input is operationally superior to variable high-peak input. The LiFePO₄ buffer stays near full charge throughout any 24-hour period, maximizing both available peak output and battery service life.
**Thermal Stack — Data Center Integration:**
| Layer | Function | Thermodynamic Role |
|---|---|---|
| Data center exhaust | Heat source | High-entropy input |
| GRG-10K hot-side manifold | Thermal absorption | Gradient establishment |
| TE conversion array | Power generation | 2–4 kW electrical work |
| GRG-10K cold side | AWG + refrigeration | Resource harvesting |
| Condensate collection | Potable water output | Waste-cold utilization |
**Manifold specification (data center variant):**
| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| Interface type | Air-to-liquid heat exchanger (primary) |
| Flow medium | Propylene glycol / water, 50/50 |
| Manifold material | 6061-T6 aluminum, chromate treated |
| Thermal resistance | ≤ 0.02 °C/W |
| Mounting | Standard hot-aisle containment rail |
| Connections | 3/4" NPT push-fit, tool-free |
| ΔT capture efficiency | 70–85% of exhaust gradient |
The TE array, power electronics, axial flux generator, battery, and grid interface are mechanically identical across both variants. Only the hot-side collection interface changes.
