## 3. Core System Specifications
### 3.1 Thermoelectric Conversion Module
The thermoelectric stage requires no moving parts, no fuel, and produces electricity directly from temperature difference. It is thermally agnostic to heat source — solar thermal, data center exhaust, geothermal, industrial waste heat, or any combination.
**Primary Material: Bismuth Telluride (Bi₂Te₃)**
-	Figure of merit ZT: 1.0–1.2 at 300K
-	Seebeck coefficient: ~200 μV/K
-	Operating range: cold side 20–40°C, hot side 60–120°C - Form factor: segmented legs, 20mm × 20mm × 5mm
**Secondary Material: Magnesium Silicide (Mg₂Si)**
-	ZT: 0.7–1.0
-	Cost: ~$4/kg versus $110/kg for Bi₂Te₃
-	Hot side segments for thermal stability
-	Enables cost-effective large-scale deployment
**Module array:** 256 thermoelectric couples in 16×16 configuration, 400 cm² active area.
The governing output variable is **heat flux (W/m²)**, not temperature difference alone. A large ΔT across a thermally resistive interface produces less power than a moderate ΔT with high thermal throughput. Thermal coupling quality — contact resistance, forced convection management, and thermal mass buffering — determines whether rated output is achieved in field conditions. This is the primary engineering variable to control during installation and commissioning.
Operating across a 60°C differential with well-coupled interfaces, baseline output is **850W continuous per array**. At 40°C differential (typical data center variant), output scales to approximately **600W per array** — lower peak, but maintained continuously around the clock. Real-world Bi₂Te₃ conversion efficiency runs 4–7%; system-level output figures reflect the full generation stack including the axial flux stage, not TE conversion efficiency in isolation.
### 3.2 Axial Flux Motor-Generator
**Stator (PCB-Based Construction)**
| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| Construction | 6-layer PCB, high-Tg FR-4 |
| Outer diameter | 320 mm |
| Slots / Poles | 36 slots, 42 poles |
| Winding type | Fractional-slot concentrated (q = 0.286) |
| Turns per coil | 28 |
| Phase resistance | 0.8 Ω |
| Operating frequency | 400 Hz electrical |
PCB stator construction eliminates iron core losses, enables automated manufacturing, and allows field replacement without specialized tooling. A damaged stator board can be replaced by any technician with basic electronics skills.
**Rotor (Halbach Array)**
| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| Magnet material | NdFeB N52 |
| Remanence | 1.48 T |
| Configuration | 4-segment Halbach per pole |
| Substrate | Carbon fiber reinforced polymer |
| Mass | 4.2 kg |
**Magnetic Bearing System:** Zero mechanical friction through 5-degree-of-freedom active magnetic levitation. Efficiency: 97–98%. Noise: under 35 dB. Maintenance interval: 5 years minimum.
**Deployment Tier Note:** The magnetic levitation bearing system is specified for the Advanced Unit. A Rugged Fallback Variant using conventional precision ball bearings (SKF 6208-2RS or equivalent) is available for deployments where field repair capability is limited and 95% reliability is preferable to 98% efficiency. The fallback variant accepts the same PCB stator and Halbach rotor with a modified bearing housing; efficiency drops to approximately 93–94% and maintenance interval shortens to 2–3 years, but any technician with a bearing press can service it. Specify variant at procurement.
