## 4. Field Adaptation Guidelines
### 4.1 Tropical and Coastal Environments
Powder-coated 5052-H32 aluminum enclosure with chromate surface treatment. All fasteners 316 stainless steel. Conformal coating on all PCBs. Designed for 25-year service life in salt-air environments. Applicable regions: Caribbean, Pacific islands, coastal West Africa, Southeast Asia.
### 4.2 High-Wind and Hurricane Zones
Streamlined enclosure geometry with no flat wind-catching surfaces. All external protrusions low-profile dome form. Design wind speed 250 km/h. Automatic shutdown with mechanical brake at wind sensor threshold. Applicable regions: Gulf of Mexico basin, Bay of Bengal, Western Pacific typhoon corridor.
### 4.3 Desert and High-Irradiance Environments
Solar thermal collector efficiency increases significantly above 6 kWh/m²/day irradiance. System output scales with collector area — doubling collector to 8 m² increases thermoelectric output proportionally. AWG module is not recommended in arid contexts (see Section 4.6). Applicable regions: Sub-Saharan Africa, Middle East, South Asia.
### 4.4 Cold Climate Adaptation
Below 10°C ambient, thermoelectric cold-side efficiency improves. System performs well in cold climates provided the solar thermal collector maintains hot-side temperature above 60°C. Applicable regions: Highaltitude communities, northern post-conflict zones.
### 4.5 Cogeneration — Refrigeration
The cold side of the thermoelectric array operates 15–20°C below ambient. This thermal output can be directed to small-scale refrigeration — directly addressing medication storage and food preservation in offgrid medical and humanitarian contexts.
### 4.6 Cogeneration — Atmospheric Water Generation
Condensation occurs naturally on any surface held below the local dew point. Rather than treating cold-side thermal output as waste to be managed, this module harvests it as a water production mechanism at nearzero additional energy cost.
**Integration Architecture:**
A dedicated secondary cold plate (0.3–0.5 m², finned aluminum or copper) is thermally coupled to the existing cold-side heat exchanger via thermal interface material. It is mounted separately from the sealed TE array enclosure, allowing condensation exposure without risk to primary electronics. A small axial fan (12V DC, 5–10W) draws ambient air across the cold plate. Condensate collects in a sealed food-grade basin below and feeds through a three-stage filtration stack before storage.
```
[Ambient Air + Humidity]
        │
        ▼
[Cold Plate — secondary, 0.3–0.5 m²]
  Thermally coupled to TE cold-side HX
  Surface held 6–10°C below dew point
        │
   [Condensate]
        │
        ▼
[Collection Basin — sealed, food-grade HDPE]
        │
        ▼
[Filtration Stack]
  Stage 1: Sediment pre-filter (5 μm)
  Stage 2: Activated carbon block
  Stage 3: UV sterilization (254 nm, 8W)
        │
        ▼
[Potable Water Storage]
```
The filtration stack draws 15–30W total from the existing 12V DC bus.
**Control Integration:**
The STM32H7 already monitors cold-side temperature via the PT100 RTD array. One additional sensor (SHT31 humidity/temperature, ~$3) on the inlet airstream allows the firmware to calculate real-time dew point. The collection fan activates only when the cold plate surface sits below dew point by a configurable margin (default: 4°C), eliminating parasitic load during low-yield conditions. This check runs at the existing 1 Hz thermal task cadence.
**Yield by Deployment Context:**
| Deployment Context | Typical RH | Est. Yield (L/hr) |
|---|---|---|
| Caribbean / coastal islands | 75–90% | 3–5 |
| Coastal West Africa | 70–85% | 2–4 |
| Southeast Asia | 70–90% | 3–5 |
| Post-hurricane / post-typhoon zones | 80–95% | 4–6 |
| Sub-Saharan inland | 40–60% | 0.5–1.5 |
| MENA / Sahel arid | <40% | Not recommended |
*Estimates based on 0.5 m² cold plate, ΔT = 8°C below dew point, 30°C ambient.*
For a Phase 1 hospital deployment in a humid coastal context, 2–4 L/hr provides meaningful supplemental water for medication preparation, wound care, and hand hygiene without dependence on local water infrastructure.
**Combined AWG and Refrigeration Operation:**
Both cogeneration modules can operate simultaneously from the same cold-side heat exchanger, provided total cold-plate surface area is sized to 0.8–1.0 m² for combined deployment. The thermal management firmware arbitrates between the two loads based on configurable priority weights, adjusted at deployment time based on local need.
