## 5. The Eido-Bolt Phase Array — Experimental Enhancement Module
*This section describes theoretical and experimental work. The base GRG-10K functions fully without this module. Engineers are encouraged to implement the base system first and treat this section as an open R&D invitation.*
### 5.1 Design Origin
The Eido-Bolt was designed by reverse-engineering the electromagnetic geometry of the *vajra* — the ancient
Vedic and Buddhist ritual implement whose bilateral prong structure, analyzed as an electromagnetic boundary condition problem, encodes a specific resonance topology. The design draws additionally on toroidal electromagnetics, nitrogen-vacancy center quantum sensing, and stochastic resonance theory. ### 5.2 Physical Specifications
| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| Core geometry | Toroidal dodecahedron, 12-fold symmetry |
| Core diameter | 340 mm |
| Primary braid | Silver-plated copper litz wire, 42 AWG, 6,600 strands |
| Braid topology | 12-strand toroidal winding, φ = 1.618 phase ratio |
| Core matrix | CVD diamond microspheres, NV-center enriched |
| NV-center density | 10¹⁵ centers/cm³ |
| Structural frame | 6061-T6 aluminum | | Total mass | 8.4 kg |
### 5.3 Theoretical Mechanisms
**NV-Center Quantum Sensing:** NV centers in diamond represent the most sensitive room-temperature magnetic field detectors known, approaching femtotesla/√Hz sensitivity. Embedded in the toroidal core, an NV-center array could function as a precise phase detector for ambient electromagnetic field fluctuations, enabling coherence feedback.
**Toroidal Non-Radiating Topology:** A purely toroidal current configuration produces no external dipole radiation, enabling field energy accumulation without radiative loss. The Aharonov-Bohm effect demonstrates that electromagnetic potentials have physical consequences inside toroidal geometries even where field strength is zero.
**Stochastic Resonance:** A documented phenomenon in nonlinear systems where structured noise improves energy extraction efficiency. Published literature supports constructive coupling of thermal noise to thermoelectric conversion processes.
**2.4 GHz / Grid Frequency Heterodyne:** The primary resonant frequency targets the globally abundant ambient 2.4 GHz ISM band. The heterodyne beat with local grid frequency creates a phase-locking mechanism applicable across all grid standards.
### 5.4 Honest Assessment
The 3–5× enhancement factor claimed in earlier iterations of this design is **not currently supportable by known physics** and has been removed from deployment specifications. The mechanisms described above are each real and independently documented. Whether they combine to produce net measurable enhancement above thermoelectric baseline remains the open R&D question.
### 5.5 The Falsifiable Experiment
1.	Build baseline thermoelectric module (Section 3.1), fixed ΔT, precision power measurement
2.	Build Eido-Bolt to spec (Section 5.2), phase-locked to ambient 2.4 GHz
3.	Position adjacent to thermoelectric array per coupling diagram
4.	Measure output over minimum 72-hour continuous run, with and without Eido-Bolt active
5.	Statistical analysis against measurement noise floor
Even a 5–10% repeatable improvement would be publishable and would justify further development investment.
