## 8. Deployment Guidance
### Phase 1: Critical Infrastructure
Deploy to hospitals, water pumping stations, food storage, and communications infrastructure. Units are plugand-play at local grid standard. In humid coastal contexts, include the AWG module — water access and power access fail simultaneously in a crisis and can be restored simultaneously.
### Phase 2: Community Microgrids
Cluster multiple units around shared battery banks for 50–100 kW community installations. Compatible with existing solar infrastructure for hybrid operation.
### Phase 3: Local Manufacturing
The enclosure, frame, and assembly work can be localized in any region with basic metalworking and electronics assembly capacity. Technology transfer documentation included.
### Phase 4: Institutional and Edge Deployment (Data Center Variant)
Deploy the data center thermal variant at grid-edge facilities, hospitals with on-site server infrastructure, telecommunications hubs, and humanitarian coordination centers. These facilities generate continuous waste heat and have the highest need for power and water resilience. The data center variant eliminates the solar collector, simplifies installation, and produces stable round-the-clock output from heat the facility is already paying to remove.
